article.description: Ukari Figgs scored 21 points and the Portland Fire held New York to three points over the final 8:29 as they beat the Liberty 54-44 Sunday.
article.headline: Liberty held to just three points the final eight minutes
article.linkText: Portland puts clamps on ice-cold Liberty in NY
article.story:
NEW YORK (AP) -- The Portland Fire seem to be managing just fine so far without Jackie Stiles, the WNBA rookie of the year last season. Ukari Figgs scored 21 points and the Fire held the New York Liberty to three points over the final eight minutes en route to a 54-44 victory Sunday. Portland (7-8) won its third in a row and second consecutive without Stiles, who is suffering from bursitis in her right heel. The Liberty (8-8) couldn't contain Figgs, the starting point guard last season for the WNBA champion Los Angeles Sparks. The 5-foot-9 guard finished 6-for-12 from the field and made three of five 3-pointers. ''She's had to take on so many new roles with us,'' Portland coach Linda Hargrove said. ''She didn't have to be a scorer for L.A., but the more injuries we've had, the more we've asked her to score.'' The Fire also played without 6-foot-4 center and leading scorer DeMya Walker, whose mouth collided with Muriel Page's knee in the 72-66 victory Friday against the Eastern Conference-leading Washington Mystics. Crystal Robinson had 17 points and Tamika Whitmore added 10 for New York, which has lost five of its past six and three of four at home. New York could not take advantage of Portland's injuries, missing layups and putbacks. New York trailed 19-16 at halftime, its lowest first-half output in Madison Square Garden, and the second-lowest for a half in team history. ''Our trademark is to outhustle people,'' New York coach Richie Adubato said. ''We broke down in our schemes and it doesn't help when you can't put the ball in the basket. We're going to have to sit down as a staff and see how we're going to turn it around.'' The Liberty shot 32 percent from the field, and missed 11 of 17 3-point attempts. Portland held Tari Phillips and Vickie Johnson, the Liberty's top scorers, to a combined 11 points in the game. ''We didn't defend,'' Johnson said. ''We have to dig down and play as a team and have a burning desire to stop people. I don't think this has ever happened to us, that the perimeter people beat us two games in a row.'' Robinson's 3-pointer with 8:29 left gave New York a 41-40 lead. The Fire responded with a 12-0 run, ended by Whitmore's layup and free throw with 39 seconds left. Tamicha Jackson, who added nine points, scored five points in the run on a steal and layup and a three-point play. Alisa Burras added 12 points for Portland off the bench. ''When we are aggressive, we play well,'' Figgs said. ''People were getting loose balls and scoring.'' The Liberty also suffered a scoring drought in the first half, leading 16-9 with 5:34 left in the half before Portland went on a 10-0 run to end the half behind four points by Figgs. New York shot just 7-for-26 from the field in the first half, with the starters making just four baskets. Stiles was placed on the injured list Friday and will miss the game at Cleveland on Tuesday before being re-evaluated. Stiles, who began feeling the effects of bursitis during training camp in early May, sat out four games June 3-13. In the six games since then, she came off the bench to average 6.3 points in 15 minutes. ''After the back-to-back games, I just got so much pain and inflammation in it,'' Stiles said. ''It's tough when you can't explode, run and jump. I really wasn't helping the team, I was just living in the training room. ''We decided to try to get it healthier so I can contribute. It's going to need surgery probably, I have a bone that's sticking out and that is what's causing the bursitis so bad.'' Stiles is still bothered by wrist surgery in her shooting hand dating back to September. Game notes
Stiles spoke with the surgeon in New York who operated on former New York Knick Patrick Ewing's wrist. ... Portland, which won 11 games last season, finishes its three-game road trip at Cleveland. ... The Liberty low for first-half points was 15 at Houston on July 3, 1999. ... New York's low for points in a game is 41 against Miami on Aug. 6, 2000. ... Sue Wicks returned to the Liberty lineup after sitting out two games with a sprained right ankle.
